				 SPV to buy coal assets abroad
 OUR CORRESPONDENT																								New Delhi, Nov. 8: The Union cabinet today cleared the formation of a special purpose vehicle (SPV) that will acquire coal blocks overseas to augment the countrys fuel reserves.																								The SPV, to be formed by five state-run PSUs, will acquire metallurgical and thermal coal assets overseas, said finance minister P. Chidambaram.																								The proposed SPV will have an authorised capital base of Rs 10,000 crore and a paid-up capital of Rs 3,500 crore.																								Steel Authority of India Ltd and Coal India will invest Rs 1,000 crore each in the SPV, while Rashtriya Ispat Nigam Ltd, NTPC and the National Mineral Development Corporation will contribute Rs 500 crore each. Officials said if required, private players may be invited to join the SPV later. 																								The overseas investment proposals of the SPV will be cleared by a committee comprising secretaries of the ministries of steel, mines, power, finance, coal, external affairs, law amp; justice and the department of public enterprises. 																								The Union cabinet also approved the setting up of this committee of secretaries.																								The SPV will have freedom to take decisions on acquisitions involving an investment of up to Rs 1,500 crore. Any investment above this will have to be referred to the committee of secretaries and subsequently to the Cabinet.																								India plans to build a coal reserve of 500 million tonnes by 2019-2020. 
